I had always till now, a good opinion of the Courage of the Duke de Beaufort, and thought the Reflections made on him by the Duke de Nemours, proceeded rather from the hatred that was between them, than from any jut occaion; but I aw now that he did all he could to get into the Town, upon pretence of declaring for the Prince of Conde, but indeed, as I thought I had good reaon to believe, to avoid fighting. For the ret, having told you the zeal of the common people, in aiting ome enterpries of his, I ought alo to tell you how it came to pas, that they had now an other Opinion of him;
you mut know, that he not only grew weary of the War, but complain'd his Troops were expos'd to all the Hardhips of an Enemy, which the Prince of Conde could not help, having not Money to pay them, that o they might have been kept in Dicipline; however the fight being begun, as I have jut now aid, was maintain'd on both ides with uch Reolution, that 'twas not known for a good while who would have the better of it; but the Vicount de Turenne, knowing that the Marechal de la Ferte was marching with all peed poibly to join him, made uch efforts that he diappointed his hopes of haring with him in the Victory. The Barricadoes were forc'd in two places, and tho the Prince of Conde diputed their paage with an incredible obtinacy, he was in great danger of having all his men cut off. If Madamoielle de Montpenier, who was always his Friend, had not done him a great piece of Service. She eiz'd upon the Batile, a Fo •• res at the Gate de St. Antoine, and letting fly the Cannon among the Kings Troops, not regarding that he was <>
himelf, oblig'd him to make a precipitate Retreat, and alo to order Turenne to do the like.

I was of an age, as I have often aid, that I could not expect to live long; and o much the rather would not attempt to preerve my Life at the Expence of my Reputation; however what I had done, on account of this Man that had deir'd me to be his Second, gave occaion to my Enemies to reflect on me, as if I had done it for fear, and they began to count me a Coward: If I had been as much a Fool as I have been formerly, I hould have made ome michief or other on that account; but beides that my Blood was not o hot now, God firt of all, and then the King, had forbid my taking that Vengeance, we ue to call Satisfaction, and I took another way to let them know, that I had as much Courage, or more, than they that aid o. The firt occaion that offer'd me, without taking notice of any thing to thee Gentlemen, I deir'd them to go out with me to dicover the Enemy, and I carry'd them o far, that they began to mutter at me, and told me, I had certainly been hir'd by ome body, to bring them all to be murther'd; this was all as I would have had it. I told them, I wonder'd they hould dicover any fear, who had been o ready to cenure others; and making no ign of returning, I came within reach of the Enemies hot, when they were pleas'd to leave me. This gave me opportunity enough to revenge my elf. When I came back to the Camp, I told all this to their Acquaintance, and to my own Friends, how they had quitted me aoon as I came to the Enemies Quarter;
and tho ome people did not fail to tell them again, yet they thought it convenient to take no notice of it, let a Man who valu'd his life o little, as they themelves had een, hould not be always in the humour to bear their Reflections. Indeed I was very unhappy to be o much talkt of, for o mall a matter; ince the like happen'd to another Man but t'other day, and no notice at all taken of it. Every body knows, that the Marquis de Crequi having challeng'd a Collonel, the Collonel, intead of meeting him as he had appointed, goes and acquaints the Marquis his Father, who was General of the Army, and taking him with him to the place, they found the Marquis there with his Second; who being urpriz'd, as no doubt any Son would have been, to ee his Father in uch a cae; and eeing there was no way to conceal the deign, he threw himelf at his feet, and promis'd him never to attempt it more. There is nothing but good fortune and bad in the World. This Collonel was o far from hurting his Reputation, that he encreat it, and pat for a wie man; and yet I not only uffer • d in uch a cae, but had the misfortune to have everal of my Friends reflect on me as well as the ret, and I had no opportunity to tell them my mind, tho I deir'd it exceedingly; above all, an account of a certain blutring Fellow call'd Chateau Bautot, who, if we would believe himelf, was the toutet man in the Army; I had my Eye upon him, I never came into his Company but I thwarted him, upon which he grew o reerv'd, that I often found he had a great deal of patience, and eaily perceiv'd he was not uch a Bravo as he aid he was. I ought indeed to have been content to have mortify'd him in this manner, but I watcht for a further opportunity, which at lat offer'd it elf when I leat lookt for it. When I return'd to the Camp the next Campaign, I came to St. Diier one day, when there being a great many Troops in the place, I had like to have lain in the treet all night, but that at lat I found out an Hot, who by the help of a Crown procur'd me a Chamber; o I put my Baggage in and reolv'd to lodge there; I went out then to ee ome Officers
of my acquaintance, but while I was walking with them, Monieur de Chateau Bautot comes into the ame Inn, and finding there was never a Chamber but mine, makes bold to turn my Baggage out and take poeion; as oon as I came back they told me how it was, and not believing any man could be o impudent, I run up Stairs to inform my elf; I was urpriz'd to find him there who I wanted uch an occaion againt, and he was no les, when he aw who it was he was like to be concern'd with; but not giving him time to make his excue, I clapt the door to and bolted it, and told him there was no reaon I hould have the advantage of the Inn o much, becaue I happen'd to come in an hour or two before him, but I thought he bet deerv'd the Chamber who was bet able to keep it. With thoe words I drew, expecting that he would do the like; but intead of that, he told me he would not be guilty of uch an ill action; that he acknowledg'd he had abus'd me, and as a further mark of it, he would immediately remove his Baggage, if I pleas'd to let them be carried away. I was aham'd of his Cowardice, and putting up my Sword, I told him that at leat then, he hould behave himelf more modetly for the future, that I had born a great deal from him, but I hould not always take it o; that I would not ue him as he had done me; tho I had much more reaon; that I now was atisfied he had a great deal more Tongue than Courage, and I hould take occaion ome time or other to tell him o, if he did not take care to ue me better. Thus I remain'd Mater of the Chamber, which I was not a little glad of I aure you; for I mut own to you, I had rather it had been he than any Peron in the World, for tho I know I ought to forgive, yet I could not help being thoroughly pleas'd at uch an opportunity to revenge my elf. This accident however made him quit the Army, and go and erve under Mr. de Schomberg in Catalonia, he had a Troop of Hore in the Regiment de Gaion; but as he was always a man of pleaure, he left the Army to run after a Mitris, and as he was coming back again, was kill'd by the Miquelets.
